{"type":"message","id":"079a2cfb","parentId":"9c38c7e3","timestamp":"2026-03-06T15:46:50.418Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_f63tc4lHbPiVwEdYMEayDNqI","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"🦞 OpenClaw 2026.3.2 (85377a2) — I autocomplete your thoughts—just slower and with more API calls.\n\nUsage: openclaw agent [options]\n\nRun an agent turn via the Gateway (use --local for embedded)\n\nOptions:\n  --agent <id>               Agent id (overrides routing bindings)\n  --channel <channel>        Delivery channel:\n                             last|telegram|whatsapp|discord|irc|googlechat|slack|signal|imessage|feishu|nostr|msteams|mattermost|nextcloud-talk|matrix|bluebubbles|line|zalo|zalouser|synology-chat|tlon\n                             (omit to use the main session channel)\n  --deliver                  Send the agent's reply back to the selected channel\n                             (default: false)\n  -h, --help                 Display help for command\n  --json                     Output result as JSON (default: false)\n  --local                    Run the embedded agent locally (requires model\n                             provider API keys in your shell) (default: false)\n  -m, --message <text>       Message body for the agent\n  --reply-account <id>       Delivery account id override\n  --reply-channel <channel>  Delivery channel override (separate from routing)\n  --reply-to <target>        Delivery target override (separate from session\n                             routing)\n  --session-id <id>          Use an explicit session id\n  -t, --to <number>          Recipient number in E.164 used to derive the\n                             session key\n  --thinking <level>         Thinking level: off | minimal | low | medium | high\n  --timeout <seconds>        Override agent command timeout (seconds, default\n                             600 or config value)\n  --verbose <on|off>         Persist agent verbose level for the session"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1552,"aggregated":"🦞 OpenClaw 2026.3.2 (85377a2) — I autocomplete your thoughts—just slower and with more API calls.\n\nUsage: openclaw agent [options]\n\nRun an agent turn via the Gateway (use --local for embedded)\n\nOptions:\n  --agent <id>               Agent id (overrides routing bindings)\n  --channel <channel>        Delivery channel:\n                             last|telegram|whatsapp|discord|irc|googlechat|slack|signal|imessage|feishu|nostr|msteams|mattermost|nextcloud-talk|matrix|bluebubbles|line|zalo|zalouser|synology-chat|tlon\n                             (omit to use the main session channel)\n  --deliver                  Send the agent's reply back to the selected channel\n                             (default: false)\n  -h, --help                 Display help for command\n  --json                     Output result as JSON (default: false)\n  --local                    Run the embedded agent locally (requires model\n                             provider API keys in your shell) (default: false)\n  -m, --message <text>       Message body for the agent\n  --reply-account <id>       Delivery account id override\n  --reply-channel <channel>  Delivery channel override (separate from routing)\n  --reply-to <target>        Delivery target override (separate from session\n                             routing)\n  --session-id <id>          Use an explicit session id\n  -t, --to <number>          Recipient number in E.164 used to derive the\n                             session key\n  --thinking <level>         Thinking level: off | minimal | low | medium | high\n  --timeout <seconds>        Override agent command timeout (seconds, default\n                             600 or config value)\n  --verbose <on|off>         Persist agent verbose level for the session","cwd":"/home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1772812010408}}
{"type":"message","id":"4265fd0c","parentId":"079a2cfb","timestamp":"2026-03-06T15:47:23.979Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So we can send a message to an agent via CLI. That could be used to trigger the skill if the agent is configured to respond to a specific command. But the skill is user-invocable via command-dispatch: model. That means the agent can interpret natural language and decide to run the skill. So we could send a message like \"Run error-learning-loop skill\". That would be processed by the agent. However, we need to ensure the agent is running (the main agent). We can run `openclaw agent --message \"Run error-learning-loop skill\" --channel webchat --deliver`. That would create a new session? Might be messy.\n\nAlternatively, we can have the watchdog (which runs within the agent context) spawn the skill as a sub-agent. That's fine because watchdog is invoked by the agent. That's already happening. So we need to modify watchdog's `_try_invoke_learning_skill` to actually invoke the skill via `sessions_spawn`. That would require the watchdog to have access to the sessions_spawn tool (which it does if it's running within an agent). The watchdog currently runs as a Python script outside the agent? Actually the watchdog is a skill that is invoked by the agent, so it has access to the same tool set? Not exactly; the skill is executed by the agent, meaning the agent reads SKILL.md and follows instructions. The watchdog skill includes scripts that are called via exec? The watchdog orchestrator is called as a script from the skill. The script runs in a separate Python process, not within the agent's tool context. So it cannot call `sessions_spawn`. However, the skill could instruct the agent to spawn a sub-agent. That's more complex.\n\nThus we need a different approach: when an incident is emitted, we need to trigger the learning loop by sending a message to the main agent (maybe via a webhook or CLI). That's getting out of scope. The simpler solution: we can have the cron reconciliation script run the learning loop by using the same pattern as the watchdog: it runs update_index.py and also triggers guardrail promotion? Wait, guardrail promotion is done by the learning loop (step 6). That's currently only done by the agent when manually invoked. We need to automate that. So we need to create a script that replicates the learning loop steps (collect incidents, deduplicate, promote guardrails). That's essentially re-implementing the skill in Python. That's a lot of work.\n\nBut maybe we can reuse the existing skill by invoking it via `openclaw agent` with a message that triggers the skill. Let's test if the skill responds to a simple command. Let's send a test message to the main agent (ourselves) but that would create recursion. Better to test later.\n\nNow, we need to wait for the sub-agent to finish and see what they produce. They might have already thought about this and will create a proper solution.\n\nLet's check the sub-agent's progress again after 10 minutes. Let's do another sessions_history with limit 20:","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_RBUm0nDLLBRVyh0HP82jyrao","name":"sessions_history","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:a98d0427-ea71-40e5-96fc-d7350d0bce09","limit":20}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","usage":{"input":847,"output":1358,"cacheRead":41280,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":43485,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772812010419}}
{"type":"message","id":"80eee7cf","parentId":"4265fd0c","timestamp":"2026-03-06T15:47:24.049Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_RBUm0nDLLBRVyh0HP82jyrao","toolName":"sessions_history","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"sessionKey\": \"agent:main:subagent:a98d0427-ea71-40e5-96fc-d7350d0bce09\",\n  \"messages\": [\n    {\n      \"role\": \"user\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"text\",\n          \"text\": \"[Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\\n\\n[Subagent Task]: ## Task: Hardening and Automation Upgrade for `error-learning-loop` skill\\n\\nYou are a specialized sub-agent tasked with enhancing the existing skill located at `~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop`. The goal is to make the learning system **fully autonomous**, reducing the need for manual intervention when processing incidents.\\n\\nYou must implement a **dual execution strategy**:\\n1. Event‑Driven Learning (Primary)\\n2. Scheduled Reconciliation (Backup via Cron)\\n\\nBoth must coexist to guarantee system reliability.\\n\\n## Current Skill Structure\\n- SKILL.md defines manual and wrap-up modes.\\n- Scripts directory currently contains only `update_index.py`.\\n- Learning store at `~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/` includes ERRORS.md, LEARNINGS.md, INDEX.md, REPORT.md, FEATURE_REQUESTS.md.\\n\\n## Objective\\nEnsure the `error-learning-loop` can:\\n- Automatically capture incidents from all skills\\n- Process incidents into Pattern‑Keys\\n- Deduplicate semantically\\n- Promote guardrails when patterns repeat\\n- Update INDEX.md and REPORT.md automatically\\n- Detect and process incidents that were missed by triggers\\n\\n## Architecture Upgrade\\nImplement a **two‑layer automation model**:\\n\\n### Layer 1 — Event‑Driven Processing (Primary)\\nThe system must trigger learning automatically whenever any of the following occurs:\\n- A sub‑agent finishes execution\\n- A Handoff Report contains incidents\\n- agent-watchdog detects stall or deadlock\\n- A skill writes to `.learnings/ERRORS.md`\\n- A complex task finishes execution\\n\\nRequired flow:\\nemit_incident()\\n→ append .learnings/ERRORS.md\\n→ trigger error-learning-loop\\n→ rebuild INDEX.md\\n→ update REPORT.md\\n\\nAll skills must call a **unified incident interface**.\\n\\nExample interface:\\nemit_incident(\\n  pattern_key,\\n  severity,\\n  source_skill,\\n  description,\\n  evidence\\n)\\n\\nYou need to create:\\n- `scripts/emit_incident.py` – unified incident emitter that writes to ERRORS.md and triggers learning loop (if event-driven mode enabled).\\n- `scripts/event_trigger_listener.py` – a script that can be invoked by other skills to register incidents and trigger processing. It should also handle automatic invocation when Handoff Reports are detected (maybe via a wrapper function). For simplicity, we can make emit_incident also call the learning loop directly (by importing existing functions from update_index.py). However, we need to avoid circular imports. Consider refactoring common logic into a shared module.\\n\\n### Layer 2 — Scheduled Reconciliation (Cron Backup)\\nA scheduled job must run daily to ensure **no incidents remain unprocessed**.\\n\\nRecommended schedule: Monday–Friday at 1:30 PM Panama Time (America/Panama).\\n\\nThe cron task must:\\n1. Scan `.learnings/ERRORS.md`\\n2. Detect incidents not yet processed (i.e., those missing from INDEX.md)\\n3. Detect Pattern‑Keys missing from INDEX.md\\n4. Rebuild INDEX.md and REPORT.md\\n5. Promote new guardrails if thresholds are met\\n6. Generate a reconciliation summary\\n\\nThe cron job must **never overwrite previous learning history**.\\n\\nCreate:\\n- `scripts/reconcile_incidents.py` – scans ERRORS.md, LEARNINGS.md, INDEX.md, identifies unprocessed incidents, and runs the learning loop on them.\\n- `scripts/cron_reconciliation_runner.py` – wrapper that sets up environment and calls reconcile_incidents.py; also logs start/end times.\\n\\n## Incident Coverage Expansion\\nExtend Pattern‑Key coverage for common system issues (add to pattern key mapping):\\n- Model Stalls: `runtime|STALL|model|no_response`\\n- Deadlocks: `runtime|DEADLOCK|multi_agent|dependency_cycle`\\n- FIT/GAP failures: `fitgap|FAILURE|scope_missing|cannot_classify`\\n- Token overflow: `tokens|OVERFLOW|context_window|exceeded`\\n- Checkpoint failures: `recovery|FAILURE|checkpoint_missing`\\n- Security violations: `security|FLS_MISSING|apex`\\n\\nEnsure these patterns are recognized during semantic deduplication.\\n\\n## Guardrail Promotio\\n…(truncated)…\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811771474\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"I'll start by examining the current skill structure and the existing update_index.py to understand the deduplication logic. First, read the skill's SKILL.md to get the current documentation.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_XykjKTH2eKXRYHRYZolfNyso\",\n          \"name\": \"read\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"path\": \"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/SKILL.md\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811771476\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Now read the existing update_index.py to understand the deduplication and indexing logic.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_VAq3G5WtvqHgI3BfZyiiRAwc\",\n          \"name\": \"read\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"path\": \"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/scripts/update_index.py\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811779449\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Now I need to understand the existing structure of ERRORS.md and LEARNINGS.md to know how incidents are formatted. Let's examine the .learnings directory. First, check what's in there:\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_rfsPB7qPy1JezLp2CqXwOjks\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811784692\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Look at ERRORS.md format:\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_zBB3xIvXh8U9r4eSWDocOfh6\",\n          \"name\": \"read\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"path\": \"~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md\",\n            \"offset\": 1,\n            \"limit\": 50\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811791822\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Now I have a good understanding. The task is to create new scripts. Let's first refactor common logic into a shared module. I'll create a `scripts/common.py` that contains functions for parsing, deduplication, and writing incidents. We'll need to decide how the event-driven trigger works: we can have emit_incident write to ERRORS.md and then call update_index.py (or import its functions). However, we must avoid circular imports. Let's extract the functions from update_index.py that are needed for processing incidents: parse_errors_md, parse_learnings_md, deduplicate_entries, etc. But maybe we can just call update_index.py as a subprocess after emitting incident? That's simpler and avoids circular imports. However, we need to ensure idempotency: we don't want to run update_index multiple times if many incidents are emitted quickly. Could batch them? For simplicity, we can have emit_incident write to ERRORS.md and then spawn a background process that runs update_index.py after a short delay, or we could just run update_index.py directly each time (since it's lightweight). Might be okay.\\n\\nLet's first examine the existing skill's scripts directory:\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_L8aIb7sFe0OL5GPEYKOjZ5lV\",\n          \"name\": \"exec\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"command\": \"ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/scripts/\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811797379\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Now, I'll create common.py with utility functions that both update_index and emit_incident can use. First, let's understand what emit_incident needs: It needs to write a new incident entry into ERRORS.md in the correct format. The format appears to be a new entry under \\\"## Entries\\\" with a heading \\\"### Pattern-Key: ***\\\". However, ERRORS.md currently has a Pattern-Key index table at the top. The update_index.py parses entries but does not write new entries; it only reads. The learning loop (manual or wrap-up) presumably creates new entries in ERRORS.md? Actually, the learning loop writes to ERRORS.md and LEARNINGS.md. That's done by the main skill logic, not by update_index.py. We need to know how incidents are added. Let's look at the skill's main script (maybe there is a learning_loop.py). But there's only update_index.py. Perhaps the skill is invoked via the agent's internal processing, not via a script. The skill is user-invocable, but the actual logic is in the skill's step-by-step instructions in SKILL.md, executed by the agent. That means the agent writes directly to ERRORS.md using its own logic. That's not ideal for automation. We need to provide a script that can be called by other skills to add incidents.\\n\\nThus we need to create a function that appends a new incident to ERRORS.md, creating the appropriate sections if needed. We also need to update the index table? The table is probably generated by update_index.py? Actually, the table in ERRORS.md is also generated by the learning loop? Let's examine the full ERRORS.md to see if the table is manually updated. Let's read the first 100 lines:\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"call_00_FwRpGD0c6kcSDqDVQD7HSll8\",\n          \"name\": \"read\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"path\": \"~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md\",\n            \"offset\": 1,\n            \"limit\": 100\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"custom-api-deepseek-com\",\n      \"model\": \"deepseek-reasoner\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1772811812999\n    }\n  ],\n  \"truncated\": true,\n  \"droppedMessages\": false,\n  \"contentTruncated\": true,\n  \"contentRedacted\": true,\n  \"bytes\": 9713\n}"}],"details":{"sessionKey":"agent:main:subagent:a98d0427-ea71-40e5-96fc-d7350d0bce09","messages":[{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: ## Task: Hardening and Automation Upgrade for `error-learning-loop` skill\n\nYou are a specialized sub-agent tasked with enhancing the existing skill located at `~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop`. The goal is to make the learning system **fully autonomous**, reducing the need for manual intervention when processing incidents.\n\nYou must implement a **dual execution strategy**:\n1. Event‑Driven Learning (Primary)\n2. Scheduled Reconciliation (Backup via Cron)\n\nBoth must coexist to guarantee system reliability.\n\n## Current Skill Structure\n- SKILL.md defines manual and wrap-up modes.\n- Scripts directory currently contains only `update_index.py`.\n- Learning store at `~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/` includes ERRORS.md, LEARNINGS.md, INDEX.md, REPORT.md, FEATURE_REQUESTS.md.\n\n## Objective\nEnsure the `error-learning-loop` can:\n- Automatically capture incidents from all skills\n- Process incidents into Pattern‑Keys\n- Deduplicate semantically\n- Promote guardrails when patterns repeat\n- Update INDEX.md and REPORT.md automatically\n- Detect and process incidents that were missed by triggers\n\n## Architecture Upgrade\nImplement a **two‑layer automation model**:\n\n### Layer 1 — Event‑Driven Processing (Primary)\nThe system must trigger learning automatically whenever any of the following occurs:\n- A sub‑agent finishes execution\n- A Handoff Report contains incidents\n- agent-watchdog detects stall or deadlock\n- A skill writes to `.learnings/ERRORS.md`\n- A complex task finishes execution\n\nRequired flow:\nemit_incident()\n→ append .learnings/ERRORS.md\n→ trigger error-learning-loop\n→ rebuild INDEX.md\n→ update REPORT.md\n\nAll skills must call a **unified incident interface**.\n\nExample interface:\nemit_incident(\n  pattern_key,\n  severity,\n  source_skill,\n  description,\n  evidence\n)\n\nYou need to create:\n- `scripts/emit_incident.py` – unified incident emitter that writes to ERRORS.md and triggers learning loop (if event-driven mode enabled).\n- `scripts/event_trigger_listener.py` – a script that can be invoked by other skills to register incidents and trigger processing. It should also handle automatic invocation when Handoff Reports are detected (maybe via a wrapper function). For simplicity, we can make emit_incident also call the learning loop directly (by importing existing functions from update_index.py). However, we need to avoid circular imports. Consider refactoring common logic into a shared module.\n\n### Layer 2 — Scheduled Reconciliation (Cron Backup)\nA scheduled job must run daily to ensure **no incidents remain unprocessed**.\n\nRecommended schedule: Monday–Friday at 1:30 PM Panama Time (America/Panama).\n\nThe cron task must:\n1. Scan `.learnings/ERRORS.md`\n2. Detect incidents not yet processed (i.e., those missing from INDEX.md)\n3. Detect Pattern‑Keys missing from INDEX.md\n4. Rebuild INDEX.md and REPORT.md\n5. Promote new guardrails if thresholds are met\n6. Generate a reconciliation summary\n\nThe cron job must **never overwrite previous learning history**.\n\nCreate:\n- `scripts/reconcile_incidents.py` – scans ERRORS.md, LEARNINGS.md, INDEX.md, identifies unprocessed incidents, and runs the learning loop on them.\n- `scripts/cron_reconciliation_runner.py` – wrapper that sets up environment and calls reconcile_incidents.py; also logs start/end times.\n\n## Incident Coverage Expansion\nExtend Pattern‑Key coverage for common system issues (add to pattern key mapping):\n- Model Stalls: `runtime|STALL|model|no_response`\n- Deadlocks: `runtime|DEADLOCK|multi_agent|dependency_cycle`\n- FIT/GAP failures: `fitgap|FAILURE|scope_missing|cannot_classify`\n- Token overflow: `tokens|OVERFLOW|context_window|exceeded`\n- Checkpoint failures: `recovery|FAILURE|checkpoint_missing`\n- Security violations: `security|FLS_MISSING|apex`\n\nEnsure these patterns are recognized during semantic deduplication.\n\n## Guardrail Promotio\n…(truncated)…"}],"timestamp":1772811771474},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I'll start by examining the current skill structure and the existing update_index.py to understand the deduplication logic. First, read the skill's SKILL.md to get the current documentation."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_XykjKTH2eKXRYHRYZolfNyso","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/SKILL.md"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811771476},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now read the existing update_index.py to understand the deduplication and indexing logic."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_VAq3G5WtvqHgI3BfZyiiRAwc","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/scripts/update_index.py"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811779449},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to understand the existing structure of ERRORS.md and LEARNINGS.md to know how incidents are formatted. Let's examine the .learnings directory. First, check what's in there:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_rfsPB7qPy1JezLp2CqXwOjks","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811784692},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Look at ERRORS.md format:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_zBB3xIvXh8U9r4eSWDocOfh6","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md","offset":1,"limit":50}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811791822},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding. The task is to create new scripts. Let's first refactor common logic into a shared module. I'll create a `scripts/common.py` that contains functions for parsing, deduplication, and writing incidents. We'll need to decide how the event-driven trigger works: we can have emit_incident write to ERRORS.md and then call update_index.py (or import its functions). However, we must avoid circular imports. Let's extract the functions from update_index.py that are needed for processing incidents: parse_errors_md, parse_learnings_md, deduplicate_entries, etc. But maybe we can just call update_index.py as a subprocess after emitting incident? That's simpler and avoids circular imports. However, we need to ensure idempotency: we don't want to run update_index multiple times if many incidents are emitted quickly. Could batch them? For simplicity, we can have emit_incident write to ERRORS.md and then spawn a background process that runs update_index.py after a short delay, or we could just run update_index.py directly each time (since it's lightweight). Might be okay.\n\nLet's first examine the existing skill's scripts directory:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_L8aIb7sFe0OL5GPEYKOjZ5lV","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls -la ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/error-learning-loop/scripts/"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811797379},{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now, I'll create common.py with utility functions that both update_index and emit_incident can use. First, let's understand what emit_incident needs: It needs to write a new incident entry into ERRORS.md in the correct format. The format appears to be a new entry under \"## Entries\" with a heading \"### Pattern-Key: ***\". However, ERRORS.md currently has a Pattern-Key index table at the top. The update_index.py parses entries but does not write new entries; it only reads. The learning loop (manual or wrap-up) presumably creates new entries in ERRORS.md? Actually, the learning loop writes to ERRORS.md and LEARNINGS.md. That's done by the main skill logic, not by update_index.py. We need to know how incidents are added. Let's look at the skill's main script (maybe there is a learning_loop.py). But there's only update_index.py. Perhaps the skill is invoked via the agent's internal processing, not via a script. The skill is user-invocable, but the actual logic is in the skill's step-by-step instructions in SKILL.md, executed by the agent. That means the agent writes directly to ERRORS.md using its own logic. That's not ideal for automation. We need to provide a script that can be called by other skills to add incidents.\n\nThus we need to create a function that appends a new incident to ERRORS.md, creating the appropriate sections if needed. We also need to update the index table? The table is probably generated by update_index.py? Actually, the table in ERRORS.md is also generated by the learning loop? Let's examine the full ERRORS.md to see if the table is manually updated. Let's read the first 100 lines:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_FwRpGD0c6kcSDqDVQD7HSll8","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"~/.openclaw/workspace/.learnings/ERRORS.md","offset":1,"limit":100}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"custom-api-deepseek-com","model":"deepseek-reasoner","stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1772811812999}],"truncated":true,"droppedMessages":false,"contentTruncated":true,"contentRedacted":true,"bytes":9713},"isError":false,"timestam